fruits.description: Fresh organic apples sourced directly from farms. Sweet and crunchy, perfect for snacking or baking.
Premium quality bananas harvested at peak ripeness. Great for smoothies, desserts, or a healthy snack.
Juicy and flavorful mangoes, a tropical delight enjoyed across India. Perfect for eating fresh or making mango lassi.
Juicy and tangy oranges, packed with vitamin C. Perfect for fresh juice or as a refreshing snack.
Sweet and succulent grapes, perfect for snacking or adding to fruit salads. Available in green, red, or black varieties.
Juicy and nutrient-rich pomegranates, known for their antioxidant properties. Perfect for snacking or adding to salads.

vegetables.description: Fresh spinach leaves, rich in vitamins and minerals. Perfect for making palak paneer or adding to dal.
Fresh and ripe tomatoes, essential for Indian curries, chutneys, and gravies. Bursting with flavor and nutrients.
Versatile and hearty potatoes, commonly used in Indian cuisine for making aloo sabzi, samosas, and pakoras.
Fresh and pungent onions, a staple ingredient in Indian cooking. Perfect for curries, salads, and pickles.
Sweet and crunchy carrots, rich in beta-carotene and fiber. Perfect for salads, soups, or as a snack.
Fresh and versatile cauliflower, perfect for making gobi masala, aloo gobi, or adding to curries and stir-fries.

legumes.description: Highly nutritious black lentils, commonly used in dal makhani, idli, and dosa. Rich in protein and fiber.
Nutty and versatile chickpeas, essential for making chana masala, hummus, and snacks like chana chaat. Rich in protein.
Red lentils, quick-cooking and versatile, commonly used in dal, soups, and stews. Rich in protein and fiber.
Green gram, commonly known as moong dal, is a nutritious and easily digestible legume. It is used in various Indian dishes like dal, dosa, and sprouts.
Sweet and tender green peas, perfect for adding to curries, pulao, or making delicious matar paneer.
Kidney beans, also known as rajma, are a popular legume in Indian cuisine. They are used to make hearty and flavorful rajma masala.

nuts_and_seeds.description: Raw almonds, rich in healthy fats, vitamins, and minerals. Perfect for snacking or adding to dishes.
Creamy and crunchy cashews, a popular ingredient in Indian sweets (mithai) and savory dishes. Rich in healthy fats and minerals.
Roasted peanuts, a popular snack enjoyed across India. Rich in protein, fiber, and healthy fats.
Nutty and rich walnuts, packed with omega-3 fatty acids and antioxidants. Perfect for snacking or adding to salads and desserts.
Pistachios, also known as pista, are delicious and nutritious nuts. They are commonly used in Indian sweets and desserts.
Sunflower seeds are crunchy and nutritious snacks, rich in vitamin E and healthy fats. They are perfect for adding to salads, trail mixes, or enjoying on their own.

pulses.description: Split mung beans, commonly used in Indian cooking for making dal, khichdi, and sprouts. Rich in protein and fiber.
Split pigeon peas, a staple in Indian cuisine for making dal, sambar, and rasam. Rich in protein and essential nutrients.
Split Bengal gram, commonly used in Indian cooking for making dal, pakoras, and chutneys. Rich in protein and fiber.
Split red lentils, also known as masoor dal, are quick-cooking and versatile. They are commonly used in Indian dal dishes and soups.
Kabuli chana, also known as chickpeas, are creamy and nutty legumes commonly used in Indian cooking. They are used to make chana masala, hummus, and snacks.
Whole red lentils, also known as masoor whole, are nutritious legumes commonly used in Indian cooking. They are used to make dal, soups, and stews.

cereals.description: Long-grain basmati rice, known for its fragrant aroma and delicate texture. Ideal for biryani, pulao, or plain steamed rice.
Whole wheat flour, commonly used in Indian households for making chapatis, parathas, and other bread. Rich in fiber and nutrients.
Pearl millet, also known as bajra, is a gluten-free grain commonly consumed in India. It is used to make roti, bhakri, or porridge.
Finger millet, also known as ragi or nachni, is a nutritious grain rich in calcium and iron. It is used to make ragi roti, porridge, or dosa.
Fresh and sweet corn kernels, perfect for boiling, grilling, or making delicious corn dishes like bhutta or corn chaat.
Sorghum, also known as jowar, is a gluten-free grain rich in fiber and antioxidants. It is used to make roti, bhakri, or porridge.
